s for water as an all-purpose metaphor with a particularly resonance for them. Its chapters are organised around a number of particular usages of water as a means of mediation and exchange between the human and the divine, from crossing a stream to dissolving in the peaceful sea of God's love. Through analysis of such recurring tropes, this book reveals that whilst water can be used to hint at transformation of the soul, and greater access to the divine, male authors also use the very same metaphorical material to regulate such access for their female readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxWomen authors. 0aReligious literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aReligious literature, EnglishxWomen authors. 0aWater in literature. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAncrene Wisse.  aJacob's Well.  aJohn Trevisa.  aOn the Properties of Things.  aPearl.  aThe Orcherd of Syon.  aallegory.  acleanliness.  acrying.  adivine access.  afluid.  agender.  agrief.  aimmersion.  alamentation.  amateriality.  amedieval writings.  areligious literature.  asacrament.  asacrifice.  ascripture.  asoul.  atears.  atransformation.  awater metaphor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800102941?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800102941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800102941/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles